                <h2>FAQs</h2>
                <h3>What is the New York City Subway?</h3>
                <p>The New York City Subway is a rapid transit system that serves the boroughs of Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, and the Bronx. It's owned by the city government and operated by the New York City Transit Authority, a part of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority (MTA).</p>
                <h3>How old is the New York City Subway?</h3>
                <p>The New York City Subway system opened on October 27, 1904, making it the oldest public transit system in the world.</p>
                <h3>How many subway stations and miles are in the New York City Subway system?</h3>
                <p>The subway has over 472 stations and spans about 248 miles (399 km) of track, making it the longest subway system in the world.</p>
                <h3>How many lines and services does the subway have?</h3>
                <p>The New York City Subway operates 36 lines and 28 services.</p>
                <h3>How can I find the subway map?</h3>
                <p>To view the subway map, go to the official MTA website at new.mta.info, click on the "Maps" section, and choose the map for the route you want.</p>
                <h3>How can I check the subway schedule?</h3>
                <p>To check the subway schedule, visit new.mta.info, select your origin and destination, choose your preferred time, and click “Find Schedule.”</p>
                <h3>Is the New York City Subway open all day</h3>
                <p>Yes, the New York City Subway runs 24 hours a day, every day of the year.</p>
                <h3>Why should I choose the subway in New York?</h3>
